{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503687"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2067"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2067"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.03,0.53,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2067"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106772"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2067"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2067"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89252"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42447"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106772"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with his mother who is concerned about her son\u0027s behaviour. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His mother reports that he has been acting very strange for the past five days, appearing unusually happy and talkative for no clear reason and getting very little sleep. He is still getting to work and has been catching up with friends over the last two days. He has had multiple episodes like this over the past year but has never sought medical advice or been hospitalised. He tells the doctor he is now feeling better than ever. His mother describes that before the last 5 days he had been quite withdrawn, taking meals in his room and appeared to be moving and speaking slowly and that it had been more than a year since he has played basketball, something he previously loved. He tells the doctor he has good ideas for helping with climate change and is eager to explain these to them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On mental state examination, his speech is pressured, rapid and he quickly changes between conversational topics. There is no evidence of hallucinations or illusions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bipolar I disorder","Schizotypal personality disorder","Bipolar II disorder","Delusional Disorder","Hypomania"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EBipolar II disorder\u003C/strong\u003E. He demonstrates symptoms of hypomania (elevated mood, decreased need for sleep, increased talkativeness, flight of ideas) lasting for five days, which meets the criteria for a hypomanic episode. Additionally, he reports usually feeling very low, suggesting a history of past depressive symptoms. The combination of hypomanic and depressive episodes defines Bipolar II disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBipolar I disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by full manic episodes, which are more severe and impairing than what is described here. The patient\u0027s symptoms are not severe enough to cause marked impairment or require hospitalization, and have occurred for less than one week, ruling out Bipolar I.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizotypal personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by odd beliefs, magical thinking, unusual perceptual experiences, and social deficits. While the patient\u0027s ideas about climate change might seem grandiose, his presentation is more consistent with a mood disorder than a personality disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelusional Disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves non-bizarre delusions that persist for at least one month. There is no clear evidence of delusions in this case, and the patient\u0027s symptoms are better explained by a mood disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypomania\u003C/strong\u003E is a symptom, not a diagnosis. While the patient is experiencing a hypomanic episode, the correct diagnosis encompasses both the current episode and his history of depressive symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bipolar disorders are characterised by recurrent episodes of mania or hypomania and depressive symptoms.","Bipolar II disorder is characterized by hypomanic episodes and depressive episodes."],"references":["Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders. Fifth ed. Arlington, VA: American Psychiatric Association; 2013.","Culpepper L. The diagnosis and treatment of bipolar disorder: decision-making in primary care. Prim Care Companion CNS Disord. 2014;16(3):PCC.13r01609."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89252"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2067"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89252","links":{"self":